1,"stem":502,"children":503,"page":22},"Tiptap","i-mdi-file-edit-outline","\u002Fdocs\u002Fweb\u002Ftiptap","1.docs\u002Fweb\u002Ftiptap",[504],{"title":505,"path":506,"stem":507},"Snippets","\u002Fdocs\u002Fweb\u002Ftiptap\u002Fsnippets","1.docs\u002Fweb\u002Ftiptap\u002Fsnippets",{"id":509,"title":510,"authors":511,"badge":517,"body":518,"date":1245,"description":1246,"extension":1247,"image":1248,"meta":1249,"navigation":1250,"path":1251,"seo":1252,"stem":1253,"__hash__":1254},"posts\u002F3.blog\u002F2023\u002Fmultus-is-the-way-to-go-for-rook-ceph-networking.md","Multus is the way to go for Rook Ceph networking",[512],{"name":513,"to":514,"avatar":515},"Alexander Trost","https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fgalexrt",{"src":516},"\u002Fimages\u002Fprofile-picture.jpg",null,{"type":519,"value":520,"toc":1242},"minimark",[521,528,536,550,598,607,610,700,703,706,711,723,736,747,767,779,992,999,1036,1047,1057,1172,1181,1188,1196,1198,1209,1215,1235,1238],[522,523,524],"note",{},[525,526,527],"p",{},"This blog post is originally from the Koor Technologies, Inc. website which due Koor Technologies, Inc. closure in early 2024 doesn't exist anymore.",[525,529,530,531,535],{},"Have you ever wanted to add more than one network interface to your Pods? Need a safer way to connect a ",[532,533,534],"em",{},"legacy"," application to multiple network VLANs in Kubernetes? Let's see how we can achieve this for a Rook Ceph cluster.",[525,537,538,539,542,543,546,547,549],{},"Normally in Kubernetes a Pod only has a single interface to communicate on the cluster network. This is and should be enough for most applications, but for production Rook Ceph deployments it isn't good enough.\nFrom Ceph's recommendation, you should preferably use two different networks. A ",[532,540,541],{},"public network"," on which clients can and will talk to all the Ceph cluster components and the second ",[532,544,545],{},"cluster network",". The ",[532,548,545],{},", as the name might imply is used for certain Ceph cluster traffic, to be exact the Ceph OSD data replication traffic.",[525,551,552,553,563,564,567,568,571,572,575,576,579,580,583,584,586,587,590,591,593,594,597],{},"A long time ago, ",[554,555,559],"a",{"href":556,"rel":557},"https:\u002F\u002Fkubernetes.io\u002Fdocs\u002Fconcepts\u002Foverview\u002Fcomponents\u002F#kube-proxy",[558],"nofollow",[560,561,562],"code",{},"kube-proxy"," was still using ",[560,565,566],{},"iptables"," (by default at the time) to ",[532,569,570],{},"route"," traffic to service IPs, the ",[560,573,574],{},"hostNetwork"," option was a common way to increase network \"throughput\". ",[560,577,578],{},"hostNetwork: true"," does that by exposing the node's network stack to the Pod's containers. At first glance, this might sound great, but it comes with some drawbacks in the security department.\nI can still remember jokingly running ",[560,581,582],{},"shutdown"," in a ",[560,585,574],{}," Pod and, let's just say I was thankfully able to somehow power on the server again through ",[532,588,589],{},"good"," old remote management interface (IPMI). So take that ",[560,592,574],{}," mode, you can ",[532,595,596],{},"weaken"," the isolation of containers by a lot.",[525,599,600,601,603,604,606],{},"You will end up with more traffic on the ",[532,602,545],{}," than on the ",[532,605,541],{}," for a simple reason, a client needs to \"write\" data once to an OSD, but the OSD needs to talk with an X amount of other OSDs to fulfill the replication requirement of the storage pool.",[525,608,609],{},"A simplified diagram of this flow of data from a client:",[611,612,613],"mermaid",{},[614,615,619],"pre",{"className":616,"code":617,"language":611,"meta":618,"style":618},"language-mermaid shiki shiki-themes material-theme-lighter material-theme material-theme-palenight","---\ntitle: Ceph Data Replication Flow\n---\nsequenceDiagram\n    Client->>OSD1: Write data to volume\n    OSD1->>OSD2: Store one replica of this data\n    OSD1->>OSD3: Store one replica of this data\n    OSD1-->>OSD1: Write data to disk\n    OSD2-->>OSD2: Write data to disk\n    OSD2->>OSD1: Data has been saved\n    OSD1-->>OSD1: Write data to disk\n    OSD3->>OSD1: Data has been saved\n    OSD1->>Client: Write Confirmation\n","",[560,620,621,630,636,641,647,653,659,665,671,677,683,688,694],{"__ignoreMap":618},[622,623,626],"span",{"class":624,"line":625},"line",1,[622,627,629],{"class":628},"sTEyZ","---\n",[622,631,633],{"class":624,"line":632},2,[622,634,635],{"class":628},"title: Ceph Data Replication Flow\n",[622,637,639],{"class":624,"line":638},3,[622,640,629],{"class":628},[622,642,644],{"class":624,"line":643},4,[622,645,646],{"class":628},"sequenceDiagram\n",[622,648,650],{"class":624,"line":649},5,[622,651,652],{"class":628},"    Client->>OSD1: Write data to volume\n",[622,654,656],{"class":624,"line":655},6,[622,657,658],{"class":628},"    OSD1->>OSD2: Store one replica of this data\n",[622,660,662],{"class":624,"line":661},7,[622,663,664],{"class":628},"    OSD1->>OSD3: Store one replica of this data\n",[622,666,668],{"class":624,"line":667},8,[622,669,670],{"class":628},"    OSD1-->>OSD1: Write data to disk\n",[622,672,674],{"class":624,"line":673},9,[622,675,676],{"class":628},"    OSD2-->>OSD2: Write data to disk\n",[622,678,680],{"class":624,"line":679},10,[622,681,682],{"class":628},"    OSD2->>OSD1: Data has been saved\n",[622,684,686],{"class":624,"line":685},11,[622,687,670],{"class":628},[622,689,691],{"class":624,"line":690},12,[622,692,693],{"class":628},"    OSD3->>OSD1: Data has been saved\n",[622,695,697],{"class":624,"line":696},13,[622,698,699],{"class":628},"    OSD1->>Client: Write Confirmation\n",[525,701,702],{},"Sidenote: That's a reason why Ceph can appear slower in direct comparisons with other storage projects because an input\u002F \"data write\" operation is only confirmed after it has been fully replicated.",[704,705],"hr",{},[707,708,710],"h2",{"id":709},"so-where-does-multus-come-into-play-here","So where does Multus come into play here?",[525,712,713,714,722],{},"Multus allows you to attach one or more (specific) network interfaces to your Pods. Making the whole ordeal of setting a Pod's network interfaces to a Pod streamlined.\nThere are still going to be some security implications when you, e.g., attach a node's network interface to a Pod, but at least it is made transparent through ",[554,715,718,719],{"href":716,"rel":717},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fk8snetworkplumbingwg\u002Fmultus-cni\u002Fblob\u002F0c37bb043c704a730535a011a19c0bde36c1463b\u002Fdocs\u002Fquickstart.md#storing-a-configuration-as-a-custom-resource",[558],"Multus' ",[560,720,721],{},"Custom Resource Definitions",".",[525,724,725,726,729,730,735],{},"A security team could simply restrict access to these \"network definitions\" using RBAC in Kubernetes. This in combination with a ",[532,727,728],{},"policy agent"," (e.g., ",[554,731,734],{"href":732,"rel":733},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.openpolicyagent.org\u002F",[558],"Open Policy Agent (OPA)","), can help enforce certain \"network access policies\".\nFor monitoring\u002F auditing as well, you can just keep an eye on which network definitions are used by which Pods.",[525,737,738,739,742,743,746],{},"Let's assume we have a Kubernetes node with two physically connected network interfaces. Let's stick to the \"good old\" interface naming schema to keep it simple: ",[560,740,741],{},"eth0"," and ",[560,744,745],{},"eth1"," interface. :winking_face:",[525,748,749,751,752,754,755,757,758,760,761,766],{},[560,750,741],{}," is used as the \"default\" interface of the node, we will be using ",[560,753,741],{}," for the Ceph ",[532,756,541],{}," (client traffic) and ",[560,759,745],{}," for Ceph's OSD replication. For simplicity, we'll assume both networks have a ",[554,762,765],{"href":763,"rel":764},"https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FDynamic_Host_Configuration_Protocol",[558],"DHCP server"," running.",[525,768,769,770,778],{},"To get started, we need to ",[554,771,774,775],{"href":772,"rel":773},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fk8snetworkplumbingwg\u002Fmultus-cni\u002Fblob\u002Fmaster\u002Fdocs\u002Fquickstart.md#storing-a-configuration-as-a-custom-resource",[558],"create two ",[560,776,777],{},"NetworkAttachDefinitions",":",[614,780,784],{"className":781,"code":782,"language":783,"meta":618,"style":618},"language-yaml shiki shiki-themes material-theme-lighter material-theme material-theme-palenight","apiVersion: \"k8s.cni.cncf.io\u002Fv1\"\nkind: NetworkAttachmentDefinition\nmetadata:\n  name: ceph-public-net\nspec:\n  config: '{\n      \"cniVersion\": \"0.3.1\",\n      \"type\": \"host-device\",\n      \"device\": \"eth0\",\n      \"ipam\": {\n        \"type\": \"dhcp\"\n      }\n    }'\n---\napiVersion: \"k8s.cni.cncf.io\u002Fv1\"\nkind: NetworkAttachmentDefinition\nmetadata:\n  name: ceph-cluster-net\nspec:\n  config: '{\n      \"cniVersion\": \"0.3.1\",\n      \"type\": \"host-device\",\n      \"device\": \"eth1\",\n      \"ipam\": {\n        \"type\": \"dhcp\"\n      }\n    }'\n","yaml",[560,785,786,805,815,823,833,840,853,858,863,868,873,878,883,891,897,910,919,926,936,943,954,959,964,970,975,980,985],{"__ignoreMap":618},[622,787,788,792,795,798,802],{"class":624,"line":625},[622,789,791],{"class":790},"swJcz","apiVersion",[622,793,778],{"class":794},"sMK4o",[622,796,797],{"class":794}," \"",[622,799,801],{"class":800},"sfazB","k8s.cni.cncf.io\u002Fv1",[622,803,804],{"class":794},"\"\n",[622,806,807,810,812],{"class":624,"line":632},[622,808,809],{"class":790},"kind",[622,811,778],{"class":794},[622,813,814],{"class":800}," NetworkAttachmentDefinition\n",[622,816,817,820],{"class":624,"line":638},[622,818,819],{"class":790},"metadata",[622,821,822],{"class":794},":\n",[622,824,825,828,830],{"class":624,"line":643},[622,826,827],{"class":790},"  name",[622,829,778],{"class":794},[622,831,832],{"class":800}," ceph-public-net\n",[622,834,835,838],{"class":624,"line":649},[622,836,837],{"class":790},"spec",[622,839,822],{"class":794},[622,841,842,845,847,850],{"class":624,"line":655},[622,843,844],{"class":790},"  config",[622,846,778],{"class":794},[622,848,849],{"class":794}," '",[622,851,852],{"class":800},"{\n",[622,854,855],{"class":624,"line":661},[622,856,857],{"class":800},"      \"cniVersion\": \"0.3.1\",\n",[622,859,860],{"class":624,"line":667},[622,861,862],{"class":800},"      \"type\": \"host-device\",\n",[622,864,865],{"class":624,"line":673},[622,866,867],{"class":800},"      \"device\": \"eth0\",\n",[622,869,870],{"class":624,"line":679},[622,871,872],{"class":800},"      \"ipam\": {\n",[622,874,875],{"class":624,"line":685},[622,876,877],{"class":800},"        \"type\": \"dhcp\"\n",[622,879,880],{"class":624,"line":690},[622,881,882],{"class":800},"      }\n",[622,884,885,888],{"class":624,"line":696},[622,886,887],{"class":800},"    }",[622,889,890],{"class":794},"'\n",[622,892,894],{"class":624,"line":893},14,[622,895,629],{"class":896},"sBMFI",[622,898,900,902,904,906,908],{"class":624,"line":899},15,[622,901,791],{"class":790},[622,903,778],{"class":794},[622,905,797],{"class":794},[622,907,801],{"class":800},[622,909,804],{"class":794},[622,911,913,915,917],{"class":624,"line":912},16,[622,914,809],{"class":790},[622,916,778],{"class":794},[622,918,814],{"class":800},[622,920,922,924],{"class":624,"line":921},17,[622,923,819],{"class":790},[622,925,822],{"class":794},[622,927,929,931,933],{"class":624,"line":928},18,[622,930,827],{"class":790},[622,932,778],{"class":794},[622,934,935],{"class":800}," ceph-cluster-net\n",[622,937,939,941],{"class":624,"line":938},19,[622,940,837],{"class":790},[622,942,822],{"class":794},[622,944,946,948,950,952],{"class":624,"line":945},20,[622,947,844],{"class":790},[622,949,778],{"class":794},[622,951,849],{"class":794},[622,953,852],{"class":800},[622,955,957],{"class":624,"line":956},21,[622,958,857],{"class":800},[622,960,962],{"class":624,"line":961},22,[622,963,862],{"class":800},[622,965,967],{"class":624,"line":966},23,[622,968,969],{"class":800},"      \"device\": \"eth1\",\n",[622,971,973],{"class":624,"line":972},24,[622,974,872],{"class":800},[622,976,978],{"class":624,"line":977},25,[622,979,877],{"class":800},[622,981,983],{"class":624,"line":982},26,[622,984,882],{"class":800},[622,986,988,990],{"class":624,"line":987},27,[622,989,887],{"class":800},[622,991,890],{"class":794},[525,993,994,995,998],{},"Short explanation on what the ",[560,996,997],{},".spec.config"," here means:",[1000,1001,1002,1018],"ul",{},[1003,1004,1005,1008,1009,1017],"li",{},[560,1006,1007],{},"\"type\": \"host-device\""," uses the ",[554,1010,1013,1016],{"href":1011,"rel":1012},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cni.dev\u002Fplugins\u002Fcurrent\u002Fmain\u002Fhost-device\u002F",[558],[560,1014,1015],{},"host-device"," CNI plugin"," to \"Move an already-existing device into a container.\"",[1003,1019,1020,1023,1024,1027,1028,1035],{},[560,1021,1022],{},"ipam"," section, ",[560,1025,1026],{},"\"type\": \"dhcp\""," ",[554,1029,1032,1016],{"href":1030,"rel":1031},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cni.dev\u002Fplugins\u002Fcurrent\u002Fipam\u002Fdhcp\u002F",[558],[560,1033,1034],{},"dhcp"," tells the CNI to get an IP from a DHCP server.",[525,1037,1038,1039,1042,1043,1046],{},"You can run ",[560,1040,1041],{},"kubectl get network-attachment-definitions"," to confirm that both ",[560,1044,1045],{},"NetworkAttachmentDefinitions"," have been created.",[525,1048,1049,1053,1054,1056],{},[1050,1051,1052],"strong",{},"Warning",": For existing clusters, you currently can't easily switch from, e.g., \"container network\" to ",[560,1055,574],{}," mode\u002F Multus.",[614,1058,1060],{"className":781,"code":1059,"language":783,"meta":618,"style":618},"apiVersion: ceph.rook.io\u002Fv1\nkind: CephCluster\nmetadata:\n  name: rook-ceph\n  namespace: rook-ceph\nspec:\n  [...]\n  network:\n    provider: multus\n    selectors:\n      public: ceph-public-net\n      cluster: ceph-cluster-net\n  [...]\n",[560,1061,1062,1071,1080,1086,1095,1104,1110,1122,1129,1139,1146,1155,1164],{"__ignoreMap":618},[622,1063,1064,1066,1068],{"class":624,"line":625},[622,1065,791],{"class":790},[622,1067,778],{"class":794},[622,1069,1070],{"class":800}," ceph.rook.io\u002Fv1\n",[622,1072,1073,1075,1077],{"class":624,"line":632},[622,1074,809],{"class":790},[622,1076,778],{"class":794},[622,1078,1079],{"class":800}," CephCluster\n",[622,1081,1082,1084],{"class":624,"line":638},[622,1083,819],{"class":790},[622,1085,822],{"class":794},[622,1087,1088,1090,1092],{"class":624,"line":643},[622,1089,827],{"class":790},[622,1091,778],{"class":794},[622,1093,1094],{"class":800}," rook-ceph\n",[622,1096,1097,1100,1102],{"class":624,"line":649},[622,1098,1099],{"class":790},"  namespace",[622,1101,778],{"class":794},[622,1103,1094],{"class":800},[622,1105,1106,1108],{"class":624,"line":655},[622,1107,837],{"class":790},[622,1109,822],{"class":794},[622,1111,1112,1115,1119],{"class":624,"line":661},[622,1113,1114],{"class":794},"  [",[622,1116,1118],{"class":1117},"sbssI","...",[622,1120,1121],{"class":794},"]\n",[622,1123,1124,1127],{"class":624,"line":667},[622,1125,1126],{"class":790},"  network",[622,1128,822],{"class":794},[622,1130,1131,1134,1136],{"class":624,"line":673},[622,1132,1133],{"class":790},"    provider",[622,1135,778],{"class":794},[622,1137,1138],{"class":800}," multus\n",[622,1140,1141,1144],{"class":624,"line":679},[622,1142,1143],{"class":790},"    selectors",[622,1145,822],{"class":794},[622,1147,1148,1151,1153],{"class":624,"line":685},[622,1149,1150],{"class":790},"      public",[622,1152,778],{"class":794},[622,1154,832],{"class":800},[622,1156,1157,1160,1162],{"class":624,"line":690},[622,1158,1159],{"class":790},"      cluster",[622,1161,778],{"class":794},[622,1163,935],{"class":800},[622,1165,1166,1168,1170],{"class":624,"line":696},[622,1167,1114],{"class":794},[622,1169,1118],{"class":1117},[622,1171,1121],{"class":794},[525,1173,1174,1175,1180],{},"(Documentation: ",[554,1176,1179],{"href":1177,"rel":1178},"https:\u002F\u002Frook.io\u002Fdocs\u002Frook\u002Fv1.11\u002FCRDs\u002FCluster\u002Fceph-cluster-crd\u002F#multus",[558],"Ceph Cluster CRD - Multus Configuration - Rook Ceph v1.11",")",[525,1182,1183,1184,1187],{},"This will tell the Rook Ceph operator to \"attach\" the Multus network annotations to the Ceph components, no need to add anything else to the ",[560,1185,1186],{},"CephCluster"," object.",[525,1189,1190,1191,722],{},"To summarize, we can use Multus to more specifically and easily have a Rook Ceph cluster use two different networks for ",[554,1192,1195],{"href":1193,"rel":1194},"https:\u002F\u002Fdocs.ceph.com\u002Fen\u002Fquincy\u002Frados\u002Fconfiguration\u002Fnetwork-config-ref\u002F",[558],"performance reasons",[704,1197],{},[525,1199,1200,1201,1027,1206,1208],{},"Looking back at the ",[554,1202,1205],{"href":1203,"rel":1204},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Frook\u002Frook\u002Fpull\u002F975",[558],"time I implemented",[560,1207,574],{}," mode in Rook, it is still the simplest way\nto \"skip the container network\" to gain more performance (depending on the CNI encapsulation, etc., used by your Kubernetes cluster network) or expose a service to other clusters\u002F servers which \"can't be just 'loadbalanced'\u002F proxied\".",[525,1210,1211,1212,1214],{},"We are looking into improving the existing documentation and examples, to make it easier for people to use Multus, instead of ",[560,1213,574],{}," mode, with their Rook Ceph clusters.",[525,1216,1217,1218,1223,1224,1229,1230,722],{},"If you want to get a more in-depth look at what Multus can do, be sure to check out this great post by ",[554,1219,1222],{"href":1220,"rel":1221},"https:\u002F\u002Fdevopstales.github.io\u002F",[558],"devopstales"," here: ",[554,1225,1228],{"href":1226,"rel":1227},"https:\u002F\u002Fdevopstales.github.io\u002Fkubernetes\u002Fmultus\u002F",[558],"Use Multus CNI in Kubernetes - devopstales",".\nTo look at what other plug